oracle.apps.fnd.applcore.oaext.osn.util
Class OsnConverterFactory

java.lang.Object
  oracle.apps.fnd.applcore.oaext.osn.util.OsnConverterFactory

public final class OsnConverterFactory
extends java.lang.Object

Creates and initializes instances of an OsnFieldValueConverter.

A standard set of converters will be pre-loaded and can be referred to by their short name. Otherwise a converter can be loaded via its fully qualified class name.

The pre-loaded converters are:

  • BooleanConv - oracle.apps.fnd.applcore.oaext.osn.publicutil.converter.boolean.OsnBooleanConverter
  • ZeroToOnePercentConv - oracle.apps.fnd.applcore.oaext.osn.publicutil.converter.percent.OsnZeroToOnePercentageConverter
  • LookupConv - oracle.apps.fnd.applcore.oaext.osn.publicutil.converter.lookup.OsnAttributeLookupValueConverter
  • LovConv - oracle.apps.fnd.applcore.oaext.osn.publicutil.converter.lookup.OsnAttributeLookupLovConverter
  • DateLocalConv - oracle.apps.fnd.applcore.oaext.osn.publicutil.converter.date.OsnDateLocalConverter

Any converter parameters values will also be set on the created converter before it is returned.

Method Detail

getConverterInstance

public static OsnFieldValueConverter getConverterInstance(java.lang.String name,
                                                          java.lang.String parameters)
Create a new instance of a converter and have it pre-populated with the parameters provided.

Parameters:
name - either the short name of the converter or the fully qualified converter class name.
parameters - the parameters to be applied to the converter. parameters must be in pairs of name=value separated by semicolons. Values can be contained within single quotes. Single quotes in a parameter value must be encoded by putting two single quotes consecurtively. For example where a converter has the methods getParam1/setParam1/getParam2/setParam2, applying the following parameter value param1=value1;param2='myvalues''2' will result in the following statements being true: converter.getParam1().equals("value1") and converter.getParam2.equals("myvalues'2").
Returns:
the newly constructed converter with parameters populated or null if the name could not be found.
